comments.text:
I'm just going to respond to the first portion of your comment. In a way, 
post production dubbing (aka ADR) is probably used in every cinematic 
feature length film.
If you are on a remote location.... the scene still needs lighting so you 
bring generators. The generators aren't quiet so your production audio 
can't be used in the film but can be used as a guide track.
Typically they get actors back in during the post process to re do the 
lines.... sometimes even change them.
This channel revolves around the ADR process and it's been a cinematic 
process for quite some time.

comments.text:
+Cameron MacLean

Actually most people put the asterisk first. It designates a correction to 
the FOLLOWING word. Putting an asterisk at the end* of a word particularly 
in a sentence can generate confusion, as most people will have seen the 
other way and not be sure which word you're correcting. (End? Of?)

In standard English literature every form of punctuation that doesn't 
represent a break, pause, expression or separation goes before the word, 
whether in pairs or not.

Such as (brackets), "quote marks", £20 numerical designations, and 
citations.
-The Founder, 2014

(With the exception of the percentage sign, for some odd reason.)

Hence the default of new modern designations such as: #you 'rewrong, 
www.yourewrong.org/thissubpageisrepresentedbyaforwardslash, and +Cameron 
MacLean is wrong .

This is because standard English text is written left to write, and 
punctuation serves as a signpost denoting what context the following text 
is to be read under. You would only put a designation AFTER the text if you 
were reading it from right to left and therefore needed that information 
first.

Expressive punctuations such as exclamation marks and question marks go at 
the end to indicate the emotional tone such that it isn't forgotten by the 
end of the sentence, to aid in fiction and the general ease of conveying 
emotion. A good case could be made that we should put one at the start of 
the sentence too, for the same reasons already stated, which is what many 
other languages do. But alas, it is not to be.

In addition to all that, there already IS a precedent for putting an 
asterisk at the end* of a word.

*For further reference or clarification elsewhere, to avoid cluttering up 
the sentence.


I don't normally give random grammar lessons to strangers, but if you're 
going to be a smart ass and attempt to correct someone who was merely 
performing the public service of safeguarding the internet from either bad 
spelling or helping someone notice a typo that might be making them look 
stupid, you should probably know what you're talking about first.

I mean it's already a dick move. The last thing you want to be is a flaccid 
dick.
